\begin_layout Section
Diffusion MRI Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Itemize
Given the measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along all the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gradient directions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{g}_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
based on the observation that spins moving in magnetic field gradient direction
 are 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the last years, Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) has established
 itself in clinical imaging and research because it is capable of imaging
 different physical properties of living tissue in a non-invasive and non-ionizi
ng way.
 There is a modality of MRI called diffusion-weighted MRI (DW-MRI), or also
 called diffusion MRI (dMRI), that exploits the natural motion of water
 molecules undergoing Brownian motion in living biological tissues.
 Applied to human brain, it allows to infer the microscopic structure of
 the brain.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Back in time, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stejskal-tanner"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed the first a pulsed gradient spin-echo (SE) sequence.
 To study the displacement of the water molecules inside the brain, diffusion
 have to be linked to the signal intensity measured in MRI.
 Thus, two additional diffusion gradient pulses were added to the original
 SE sequence.
 The first of the two gradient pulses in this sequence introduces a phase
 shift that is dependent on the strength of the gradient at the position
 of the spin at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 After that a 
\begin_inset Formula $180Â°$
\end_inset

 RF pulse is applied to reverse the phase shift induced by the first gradient
 pulse.
 Ultimately, a second gradient pulse is applied to induce a phase shift
 dependent on the spin position at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 The first diffusion-encoding gradient causes the phase shift to vary with
 position.
 After the second diffusion-encoding gradient is applied, all spins that
 did not move will return to the their initial state.
 Therefore, if we measure the signal after the second gradient, we will
 get a high intensity signal because spins are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in-phase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, resulting in a bright pixel.
 On the other hand, if the spins have moved, they will subjected to a different
 field strength during the second pulse and therefore will not return to
 the initial state, causing a decreased intensity of the measured signal.
 The longer the displacement along a gradient direction, the lower the signal
 intensity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-diffusion-SE.png
	scale 30

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:diffusion-SE"

\end_inset

Diagram shows the pulsed gradient SE sequence used for diffusion MR imaging.
 Two diffusion-encoding gradient (
\begin_inset Formula $G_{diff}$
\end_inset

 or also denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

) pulses are added to the standard SE MR imaging sequence to introduce a
 phase shift proportional to molecular displacement along the gradient direction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=$
\end_inset

 duration of the diffusion-en- coding gradient, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=$
\end_inset

 diffusion time interval, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{phase}=$
\end_inset

 phase-encoding gradient, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{read}=$
\end_inset

 readout gradient, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{slice}=$
\end_inset

 section-selective gradient, RF=radio frequency pulse, 
\begin_inset Formula $t=$
\end_inset

 acquisition time.
 The diffusion-encoding gradient often is symbolized by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

, which is equal to the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\delta\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the gyro-magnetic ratio; thus, it represents the effective diffusion
 gradient.
 Image take from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diffusioni-MRI-for-dummies"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to represent a diffusion gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

 as a 3D vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=\gamma\delta\mathbf{g}/2\pi$
\end_inset

 whose orientation is in the direction of diffusion and its length is proportion
al to the gradient strength.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 allows to navigate in the 3D diffusion space called 
\series bold
q-space
\series default
 and denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{3}$
\end_inset

, which the coordinates are defined by the frequency wave vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 with norm 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\left\Vert \mathbf{q}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $mm^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The gradient strength, also called diffusion weighting, is usually expressed
 in term of the 
\series bold
b-value
\series default
, which is responsible of tuning the diffusion attenuation.
 It is commonly denoted with 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $b=t\left\Vert \mathbf{q}\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

 (proportional to the gradient strength and the diffusion time interval)
 and measured in 
\begin_inset Formula $s/mm^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the measured diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, or in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The application of a single pulsed gradient SE sequence as described in
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:diffusion-SE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 produces one diffusion weighted signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to one position in q-space, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:q-space"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Applying sequences by varying the strength and direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 allows data sampling of the q-space.
 In most cases, a reference image 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 is taken.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 image does not have any diffusion sensitization, i.e.
 the strength of the diffusion gradient is zero (
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0$
\end_inset

).
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a standard SE image.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-q-space.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:q-space"

\end_inset

Diffusion-weighted image (right) from signal sampling at a single point
 in 3D q-space (left).
 Brain areas where diffusion in intense in the direction of the applied
 gradient 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}$
\end_inset

 appear darker because of a decrease in the measured signal that results
 from dephasing.
 Image take from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diffusioni-MRI-for-dummies"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally and in general, the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is normalized by using the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 signal to get the signal attenuation 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=S\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)/S_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In was shown that there is a Fourier relationship between the signal attenuatio
n 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and the diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)$
\end_inset

, which gives the probability of any displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 during the diffusion time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{3}}p\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi i\mathbf{q}^{T}\mathbf{r}\right)d\mathbf{r}\label{eq:FFT-relationship-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Diffusion Tensor Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal direction of diffusion in the tissue can be represented with
 a method called 
\series bold
D
\series default
iffusion 
\series bold
T
\series default
ensor 
\series bold
I
\series default
maging (DTI).
 It was rigorously formalized for the first time in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DTI-1,DTI-2,DTI-3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which were pioneer works in the field.
 Assuming Gaussian diffusion, DTI builds the apparent water self-diffusion
 tensor at each voxel.
 The structure of the tensor allows to infer the orientation of the diffusion
 compartments within the voxel.
 For example, the major eigenvector of the tensor is parallel to the principal
 fiber orientation, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DTI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-dti.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:DTI"

\end_inset

DTI ellipsoids, prolate, oblate, and spherical tensors.
 Water molecules diffusion along fibers.
 The diffusion tensor model captures this orientated diffusion process with
 the diffusion ellip- soid.
 Here, the FA of the illustrated tensor is approximately 0.7.
 The tensor can also be oblate if the first two eigenvalues are equal or
 spherical if all three are equal.
 Figure taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusion signal from a single Gaussian diffusion compartment within
 a voxel is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},b\right)=exp\left(-b\mathbf{g}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{D}\mathbf{g}_{i}\right),\;\;\;1\leq i\leq n,\label{eq:dti-signal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the normalized diffusion signal magnitude for the DEO 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion tensor mathematically written as a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 symmetric and positive definite matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{D}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
D_{xx} & D_{xy} & D_{xz}\\
D_{xy} & D_{yy} & D_{yz}\\
D_{xz} & D_{yz} & D_{zz}
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

The diffusion tensor can be decomposed into its eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

 and eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

 using traditional matrix diagonalization methods or they can be obtained
 direcly from the tensor values as it was documented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DTI-formulas-1,DTI-formulas-2,DTI-formulas-3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The largest eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 gives the the Principal Diffusion Direction (PDD) of the tensor.
 The rest of the eigenvectors determinate the orthogonal planes to it, see
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DTI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 These eigenvectors and eigenvalues not only determinate the shape of the
 tensor, but they are closely related to brain tissue properties.
 For example, the largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the Axial Diffusivity (AD), while 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\lambda_{2}+\lambda_{3}}{2}$
\end_inset

 give information about the Radial Diffusivity (RD).
 Besides, from the diffusion tensor eigenvalues, several spherical measures
 can be extracted such as the 
\series bold
M
\series default
ean 
\series bold
D
\series default
iffusivity (MD) or the 
\series bold
F
\series default
ractional 
\series bold
A
\series default
nisotropy (FA), among others.
 Both are given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
MD=\frac{\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}+\lambda_{3}}{3}, &  & FA=\frac{3}{2}\sqrt{\frac{\left(\lambda_{1}-\lambda_{2}\right)^{2}+\left(\lambda_{1}-\lambda_{3}\right)^{2}+\left(\lambda_{2}-\lambda_{3}\right)^{2}}{\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{1}^{2}}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Regardless of these measures have been widely used in publications within
 the field, it is important to note that the Gaussian diffusion assumption
 implies that there can only be a single fascicle per voxel.
 Thus, metrics maps resulting from DTI have one single value per voxel.
 An extension of these metrics to handle multiple fascicles will be discussed
 later in Chapter 2, and they constitute an essential component of this
 work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-DTI-metrics.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:DTI-metrics"

\end_inset

Graphic Illustration of DTI.
 (a) Example of the obtained diffusion tensor image resulted to fit DTI
 at every voxel to real human brain dMRI.
 Tensors are colored with the PDD using the color code 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y,z\right)\rightarrow\left(r,g,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 (b) FA map obtained from computing the FA value of the diffusion tensor
 at each voxel.
 Dark areas represent voxels with low FA while high intensity voxels represent
 high FA.
 (c) MD map computed from the tensor field.
 Bright areas indicate areas high high mean diffusivity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
HARDI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was used a strategy for dense sampling on the sphere using a single b-value.
 The term 
\series bold
H
\series default
igh 
\series bold
A
\series default
ngular 
\series bold
R
\series default
esolution 
\series bold
I
\series default
maging (HARDI) was coined for this particular sampling strategy.
 HARDI is very similar in nature to the standard sampling for DTI.
 However, HARDI involves a larger number of unique diffusion-weighting gradient
 directions.
 Moreover, HARDI is not always a spherical sampling, but there also exists
 more sampling schemes of the 3D diffusion space, see Figure .
 For example,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cartesian HARDI: Sampling of the whole q-space on a dense 3D cartesian grid.
 This is usually associated with the DSI method, see Section 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
poner seccion
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Single-shell HARDI: This sampling is a spherical sampling of the q-space
 for a single b-value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multi-shell HARDI: Same as single-shell but using multiple different b-values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-HARDI-schemes.png
	scale 55

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:HARDI-schemes"

\end_inset

Different HARDI schemes for sampling the q-space.
 (a) Cartesian sampling designed for DSI, see seccion 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
poner seccion
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 (b) Single-shell spherical sampling.
 (c) Multi-shell spherical sampling.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HARDI was originally proposed to address the limitation of DTI for solving
 crossing fiber configurations.
 It is frequently accompanied of reconstruction methods more sophisticated
 than DTI, see Section 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
poner seccion
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In fact, some methods require a specually designed HARDI acquisition strategy
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HYDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Overall, it may be said that HARDI is not only important for solving the
 crossing fiber problem, but also for improving tractography, providing
 anisotropy metrics beyond FA and, therefore, for obtaining a reliable tractomet
ry analysis as we will describe in the incoming sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Local Modeling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Multiple Fascicle Reconstruction Methods
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Diffusion Orientation Transform (DOT) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a technique that provideds a direct estimation of displacement probability
 surfaces at each voxel from the dMRI data.
 DOT uses the Fourier relationship between the signal attenuation and the
 diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)=\oint_{\mathbf{\mathbb{S}^{2}}}\int_{0}^{\infty}E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi irq\hat{\mathbf{q}}^{T}\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)q^{2}dqd\hat{\mathbf{q}},\label{eq:propagator-signal-fourier-relationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=q\hat{\mathbf{q}}\in\mathbb{Q}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mathbf{r}}=r\hat{\mathbf{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 It is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 attenuates mono-exponentially, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=exp\left(-4\pi^{2}tq^{2}D\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion coefficient or diffusivity profile.
 In other words, DOT transforms water diffusivity profiles into displacement
 probability profiles.
 Finally, the dODF can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 by means of the radial projection as in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffusion-propagator-to-dODF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 DOT faces some limitations regarding the HARDI sampling schemes with finite
 support, truncated spherical harmonics and the mono-exponential attenuation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT-revisited"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed an extension of the DOT method that mitigates these limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Esto lo quit[e de arriba
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Therefore,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)=exp\left(-4\pi^{2}tq^{2}D\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)\right),\label{eq:mono-exponential-attenuation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion coefficient or diffusivity profile.
 In other words, DOT transforms water diffusivity profiles into displacement
 probability profiles.
 In addition, DOT uses the following expasion in terms of spherical wave
 functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
exp\left(-2\pi irq\hat{\mathbf{q}}^{T}\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)=\sum_{l=0}^{l_{max}}\sum_{m=-l}^{l}\left(-i\right)^{l}j_{l}\left(2\pi rp\right)Y_{lm}\left(\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)Y_{lm}^{*}\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right),\label{eq:plane-wave-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{lm}$
\end_inset

 are respectively the spherical Bessel function of the first kind and the
 spherical harmonic of order 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 can be computed using Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mono-exponential-attenuation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which can be used to compute
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{l}\left(r,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)=,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which can be expanded in terms of spherical harmonics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{l}\left(r,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right)=\sum_{l^{'}=0}^{l_{max}}\sum_{m=-l^{'}}^{l^{'}}a_{l^{'}m^{'}}Y_{l^{'}m^{'}}\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finally, the dODF can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 by means of the radial projection as in Equation 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inserta ecuacion 2.16 de la tesis de Rick
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
DOT faces some limitations regarding the HARDI sampling schemes with finite
 support, truncated spherical harmonics and the mono-exponential attenuation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT-revisited"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed an extension of the DOT method that mitigates these limitations.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Limitations of DTI came when several fiber populations are present in a
 voxel.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The term fixel refers to a specific fibre bundle within a specific voxel.
 It was proposed by the MRtrix technical team 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fixel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is consistent with the definition of pixel and voxel, which are terms
 commonly used in the field.
 The terms pixel and voxel are abbreviations of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

picture element
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

volume element
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or smallest element within a 2D and 3D image, respectively.
 On the other hand, fixel refers to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fibre bundle element
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the smallest discrete component of a fibre bundle.
 Each fixel is completely determinated by the voxel in wihch it resides,
 the estimated mean orientation of the underlying fibres attributed to that
 bundle, a fibre density (or partial volume fraction), and other metrics.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any diffusion model or representation that is capable of fitting multiple
 anisotropic elements to each image voxel is estimating fixels.
 It is important to say that fixel term should not be confused with other
 interpretations like, for example, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fibre bundle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fascicle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging (DSI) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DSI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a MRI technique that employs the diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to describe the diffusion process in each voxel.
 It uses Fourier relationship between a, sufficient dense, cartesian sample
 of the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in the q-space and the diffusion probability density function such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)=\mathcal{F}^{-1}\left\{ S\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)\right\} =\int_{\mathbb{Q}^{3}}S\left(\vec{\mathbf{q}},t\right)exp\left(i\vec{\mathbf{q}}\cdot\vec{\mathbf{r}}\right)d\vec{\mathbf{q}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the 3D inverse Fourier transform.
 Then, the dODF 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 can be reconstructed by radially projecting 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\vec{\mathbf{r}},t\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Psi\left(\hat{\mathbf{r}}\right)=\intop_{0}^{\infty}p\left(r\hat{\mathbf{r}},t\right)r^{2}dr,\label{eq:diffusion-propagator-to-dODF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbf{\mathbb{R}_{0}^{+}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{r}}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 DSI can detect the multiple fascicle orientation within a voxel.
 However, it requires strong gradients (
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq b\leq20,000$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $s/mm^{2}$
\end_inset

) as well as long acquisition time to measure hundreads of directions and
 b-values.
 That's why is of real interest in clinical applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Q-Ball Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Q-Ball Imaging (QBI) is a method that employ the Funk-Radon transform
 (FRT) on HARDI derived data to obtain a diffusion ODF (dODF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)=\int_{\varOmega\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)}S\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}},t\right)d\hat{\mathbf{q}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varOmega\left(\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right)=\left\{ \hat{\mathbf{q}}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}\,|\,\hat{\mathbf{q}}\perp\hat{\mathbf{u}}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{q}}=\mathbf{q}/q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}\in\mathbb{Q}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 FRT uses the fact that the diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(\hat{\mathbf{q}},t\right)$
\end_inset

 is maximal in the directions perpendicular to the underlying fascicles,
 see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:funk-radon-transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The dODF can properly represent the presence and orientation of multiple
 crossing fascicles.
 However, the resulted dODF is artificially smooth and inflated compared
 to the true diffusion ODF.
 Problematically, this same feature causes QBI to poorly distinguish fibers
 crossing at tight angles.
 Some modifications and generalizations to QBI have been published to try
 to achieve most of the QBI limitations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-SWT,QBI-CSA,GQI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-SWT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed a spherical wavelet transform to sharpen and denoise the dODF.
 Additionally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-CSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the dODF is normalized using a solid angle factor.
 Finally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GQI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 a generalization of the q-ball imaging was proposed using a direct transform
 of the raw signal.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-funk-radon-transform.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:funk-radon-transform"

\end_inset

Illustration of the FRT that QBI uses to reconstruct the dODF using the
 diffusion MRI measured signal.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spherical Deconvolution Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
S
\series default
pherical 
\series bold
D
\series default
econvolution (SD) is one of the most popular techniques to recover the principal
 diffusion directions from the dMRI data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 SD considers the measured HARDI signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as the convolution of the response function, which is an axially symmetric
 kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that represents a single-fiber response, with the expected true 
\series bold
f
\series default
iber 
\series bold
O
\series default
rientation 
\series bold
D
\series default
istribution 
\series bold
F
\series default
unction (fODF) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:signal-convolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left(\mathbf{q}\right)/S_{0}=\left(F\varotimes R\right)\left(\mathbf{q}\right)=\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)R\left(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v},\;\;\;\mathbf{q}\in\mathbb{Q}^{3},\label{eq:signal-convolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the non-diffusion weighted image.
 Therefore, the fODF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be reconstructed by solving the following optimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{F}{argmin}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\bigl\Vert S\left(\mathbf{q}\right)-S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)R\left(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v}\bigr\Vert^{2},\label{eq:signal-deconvolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-b.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:signal-convolution"

\end_inset

Convolution assumption in q-space between the response 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and the fODF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\;\;\;$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-a.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:signal-deconvolution"

\end_inset

Spherical deconvolution intuition to improve angular resolution of ODF reconstru
ction.
 Assuming a particular response function, the deconvolution will remove
 the âblurryâ part of the diffusion ODF to obtain a sharp fiber ODF that
 better captures the underlying fiber populations.
 Hence, a better angular resolution can be obtained, as illustrated in 
\begin_inset Formula $45Â°$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $60Â°$
\end_inset

 crossing in the bottom of the figure.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustration of the convolution and deconvolution of a signal.
 Imagen taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem given by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:signal-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is usually solved by using 
\series bold
S
\series default
pherical 
\series bold
H
\series default
armonics (SH) representation (see Anexo) of the measured signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and the fODF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 For every harmonic order 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq l\leq l_{max}$
\end_inset

, let's denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{l},\mathbf{F}^{l}\in\mathbb{R}^{2l+1}$
\end_inset

 the vector of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2l+1\right)$
\end_inset

 representing the 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-th order SH decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Analogously, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{l}\in\mathbb{R}^{\left(2l+1\right)\times\left(2l+1\right)}$
\end_inset

 be the matrix representing the 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-th order rotational harmonic decomposition of the response 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The spherical convolution operation in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:signal-convolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can thus be reduced to simple matrix operation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{S}^{l}=\mathbf{R}^{l}\mathbf{F}^{l}.\label{eq:spherical-convolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the problem of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:signal-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is reduced to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{F}^{l}}{argmin}\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert \mathbf{R}^{l}\mathbf{F}^{l}-\mathbf{S}^{l}\right\Vert _{2}^{2},\label{eq:spherical-deconvolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}^{l}$
\end_inset

 is the unknown vector of coefficients of the fODF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 However, this SD technique is ill-posed and affected by noise.
 Later in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CSD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was introduced a modification to SD called 
\series bold
C
\series default
onstrained 
\series bold
S
\series default
pherical 
\series bold
D
\series default
econvolution (CSD) that preserves the angular resolution while remaining
 robust to noise effects.
 In CSD a non-negativity constraint on the estimated fODF is included into
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:spherical-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\mathbf{F}^{l}}{argmin}\frac{1}{2}\left\Vert \mathbf{R}^{l}\mathbf{F}^{l}-\mathbf{S}^{l}\right\Vert _{2}^{2}\;\;\;subject\;\;to\;\;\mathbf{R}^{l}\mathbf{F}^{l}\geq\mathbf{0}.\label{eq:constrained-spherical-deconvolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This relies in the fact that negative fibre orientation densities are physically
 impossible.
 Besides, this constraint eliminates the need for low-pass filtering the
 obtained fODF.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternate solution to Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:signal-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is to approximate the fODF using polinomial functions.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "STD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 it was shown that any homogeneous polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of order 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed into linear combinations of the same order such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{r}\lambda_{i}f_{l}^{d},\;\;\;\mathbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{l},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{l}=\sum_{i=1}^{l}a_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the polynomial rank and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

is the polynomial dimension.
 This decomposition is known as
\series bold
 S
\series default
ymmetric 
\series bold
T
\series default
ensor 
\series bold
D
\series default
ecomposition (STD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SD-STD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 because polynomials are directly related to symmetric tensors.
 With this in mind, the fODF 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 can be approximated using an equivalent lower-rank approximation such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)\simeq\sum_{i=1}^{\widetilde{r}}\gamma_{i}f_{i}^{d}=\sum_{i=1}^{\widetilde{r}}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}\right)^{d},\;\;\;\widetilde{r}<r,\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{3},\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}.\label{eq:fODF-approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The number of fascicles to be estimated is determined by the approximation
 rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{r}$
\end_inset

, and each fiber aligned in direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is identified with a linear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{v}\right)^{d}$
\end_inset

.
 In the end, substituting Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fODF-approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:signal-deconvolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 leads to the following non-linear optimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\alpha_{j}}{min}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\bigl\Vert S\left(\mathbf{q},b\right)-S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}\left(\boldsymbol{\alpha}_{i}\cdot\boldsymbol{v}\right)^{d}R\left(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v}\bigr\Vert^{2}.\label{eq:symmetric-tensor-decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is solved for the coefficients of the linear-forms, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 coefficients for each fascicle; all of them are estimated directly from
 the measured dMRI signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 This method avoids the complexity of extracting the orientations from the
 ODF and can recover complex fascicles configuration using less parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multi-Tensor Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-tensor representation or Multi-tensor Model (MTM) is a natural extension
 of DTI, where orientated diffusion along the fascicles is represented with
 a mixture of Gaussian distributions at each voxel such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},b\right)=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\alpha_{k}exp\left(-b\mathbf{g}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{D}_{k}\mathbf{g}_{i}\right).\label{eq:multi-tensor-representation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially, the expectation maximization algorithm was used to solve Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:multi-tensor-representation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, this algorithm is unable to handle physiological constraints on
 the eigenvalues.
 Later, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MTM-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 a gradient descent scheme with multiple restarts was employed to solve,
 by considering the mentioned constraints, the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:multi-tensor-representation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{k}$
\end_inset

 and volume fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

, while the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{k}$
\end_inset

 where specified a priori or restricted to a particular range.
 However, these and others 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MTM-2,MTM-3,MTM-4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed methods to solve the MTM have been reported to be numerically
 challenging and unstable.
 Later, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pre-DIAMOND"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was provided the first analytical demonstration that when using a diffusion
 MRI acquisition with only one non-zero b-value, such as in conventional
 single-shell HARDI acquisition, a co-linearity in model parameters makes
 the precise model estimation impossible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffusion Bases Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
D
\series default
iffusion 
\series bold
B
\series default
ases 
\series bold
F
\series default
unctions (DBF) is a dictionary-based method for the estimation of the intra-voxe
l configuration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DBF"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \Phi_{j}\right\} _{j=1}^{J}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 basis functions are generated using the radially symmetric diffusion tensor.
 Then, the diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in matrix form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\Phi\mathbf{\alpha},\label{eq:DBF-matrix-form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left(S\left(\mathbf{g}_{1},b\right),\ldots,S\left(\mathbf{g}_{n},b\right)\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of diffusion signal samples, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}^{J}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of contributions for each basis function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times J}$
\end_inset

 is the dictionary containing all 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 basis functions of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-DBF-2D-example.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:DBF-2D-example"

\end_inset

2D schema of DBFs.
 The blue lines correspond to a dictinoary with 
\begin_inset Formula $J=5$
\end_inset

 basis functions.
 (a) Continuous-blue line shows the DBFs generated by an uniformly distributed
 tensor basis with 
\begin_inset Formula $J=5$
\end_inset

.
 The doted-red line represents the normalized diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left(\mathbf{q}\right)$
\end_inset

 generated by an arbitrary diffusion tensor.
 In this case, the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is expected to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\left(0,0,1,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 (b) Schema for two fiber case, the dotted-red lines represent the signals
 for two arbitrary tensors, which their half-addition of both signals are
 shown in the cross-marked black line.
 For this case, the solution is expected to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\left(0,0,0.5,0,0.5\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DBF"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DBF-matrix-form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 using a basis pursuit technique, which compute the solution by means of
 non-negative least-squares of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\alpha}{min}\left\Vert \alpha\right\Vert _{1}=\sum_{j}\alpha_{j}\;\;\;subject\;\;to\;\;S=\Phi\alpha,\;\;\;\alpha_{j}\geq0,\;\;\;j=1,\ldots,J.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
MRDS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most appropiate representation and modeling of multiple fascicles traversing
 the same voxel remains unclear.
 Actually, there is a multi-tensor based method, which represents multiple
 fascicles with multi-tensors fitted using the 
\series bold
M
\series default
ulti
\series bold
 R
\series default
esolution 
\series bold
D
\series default
iscrete 
\series bold
S
\series default
earch (MRDS) approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MRDS"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 MRDS is capable of providing individual diffusion profiles as well as the
 orientation of the fasicles.
 MRDS is a general framework for estimating parameters in a multi-compartment
 representation.
 The normalized DWI signal attenuation 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}=S_{i}/S_{0}$
\end_inset

 at each voxel of a multi-compartment model is represented as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{i}=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\alpha_{k}\Phi_{i}\left(\zeta_{k}\right)+\eta_{i},\;\;\;i=1,2,\ldots,n,\label{eq:multi-compartment-model-representation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of compartments, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 the number of DEOs 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
define arriba DEO (Diffusion Enconding Directions)
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha_{k}>0\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 denotes the compartment sizes (volume fractions) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents the signal noise.
 Besides, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}\left(\zeta_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the signal response of the compartment function for the DEO 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 defined by the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{k}$
\end_inset

, which is a vector in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{k}=\left(\theta_{k},\xi_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{k}=\left(\theta_{k}^{z},\theta_{k}^{a}\right)$
\end_inset

 define the zenith (elevation) and azimuth angles of the PDD of the compartment.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of parameters associated with the tissue properties for the
 compartment 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming Gaussian noise, the error function to be minimized is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon\left(N,\alpha,\theta,\xi,E\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{N}\alpha_{k}\Phi_{i}\left(\zeta_{k}\right)-E_{i}\right)\label{eq:MRDS-error-function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that in the particular case of a 
\series bold
m
\series default
ulti-
\series bold
t
\series default
ensor 
\series bold
m
\series default
odel (MTM) representation we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}\left(\zeta_{k}\right)=exp\left(-b_{i}g_{i}^{T}D_{k}g_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}=\left(\lambda_{k}^{\parallel},\lambda_{k}^{\perp}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents the axial (
\begin_inset Formula $\parallel$
\end_inset

) and radial (
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

) diffusivities.
 The PDD 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{k}$
\end_inset

 defines the rotation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R\left(\theta_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{k}=D\left(\theta_{k},\xi_{k}\right)=R\left(\theta_{k}\right)\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\lambda_{k}^{\parallel} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{k}^{\perp} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \lambda_{k}^{\perp}
\end{array}\right]R^{T}\left(\theta_{k}\right).\label{eq:tensor-matrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, the proposed MRDS algorithm consists in the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimation of the orientations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \theta_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and the compartment sizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 for fixed diffusion parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimation of the diffusion parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \xi_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \theta_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \alpha_{k}\right\} _{k=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeat previous steps until convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The output of the previos steps consists of the best possible configurations
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 fascicle orientations and diffusivities.
 Finally, in this step a model selector determinates the optimal value for
 the number of bundles for the considered voxel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MRDS has proved to be more robust to noise and crossing fascicles than other
 methods like DIAMOND and CSD 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MRDS-rats"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
DIAMOND
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DIAMOND stands for Characterizing the 
\series bold
DI
\series default
stribution of 
\series bold
A
\series default
nisotropic 
\series bold
M
\series default
icr
\series bold
O
\series default
-structural e
\series bold
N
\series default
vironments with 
\series bold
D
\series default
iffusion-weighted imaging (DIAMOND) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DIAMOND"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This method propose a statistical distribution model of the diffusion in
 which the signal is modeled arising from each spin-packet with a 3D diffusion
 tensor.
 The presence of multiple fascicles in each voxel is modeled with a mixture
 of peak-shaped matrix-variate Gamma distribution of spin-packets.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This method consider that the measured signal can be described by a sum
 of signals arising from a large number of individual spin-packets within
 the voxel.
 Each spin-packet undergoes homogeneous 3D Gaussian diffusion represented
 by a diffusion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

, whose contribution to the signal for a DEO 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}exp\left(-b_{i}\mathbf{g}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{D}\mathbf{g}_{i}\right)d\mathbf{D}.
\]

\end_inset

A matrix-variate distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\mathbf{D}\right)$
\end_inset

 determinates the fraction of spin-packets described by a same tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the DIAMOND representation is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},t\right)=S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{D}}P\left(\mathbf{D}\right)exp\left(-b_{i}\mathbf{g}_{i}^{T}\mathbf{D}\mathbf{g}_{i}\right)d\mathbf{D},\label{eq:DIAMOND}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{D}$
\end_inset

 is the set of symmetric positive-definite 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 When a voxel is composed of one single fascicle, Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DIAMOND"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 matches with DTI.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the whole, one of the main challenges in building accurate models is
 to find a balance between the complexity and the number of parameters of
 the model.
 Models with few parameters have a low level of complexity and are easier
 to fit.
 However, these models tend to underfit the data because they do not have
 enough flexibility to capture variations in the diffusion signal.
 On the other hand, high complexity models are more capable of capturing
 variations in the diffusion signal and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
have many parameters to tune and tend to overfit the data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tractography
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
They can be classified into two categories: (1) Line propagation techniques
 or denominated as local techniques, and (2) energy minimization techniques
 also known as global techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Several frameworks to perform tractography are available such as MRtrix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MRtrix"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, DIPY 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DIPY"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Camino, among others.
 These software packages implement some of the most popular methods in the
 state-of-the-art.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mention that local techniques are bias by noisy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mention that there are filtering techniques like COMMIT or LiFE.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffusion tractography or white matter fiber tracking is a process, where
 three-dimensional axonal trajectories can be tracked using information
 from dMRI data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Captured pathways - also known as 
\series bold
streamlines
\series default
 or 
\series bold
tracks
\series default
 - are represented as curves in a 3D space, i.e.
 a streamline is mathematically written as a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \mathbf{p}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\right\} _{i=1}^{M}$
\end_inset

, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:streamline-tractogram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 containing all these streamlines is called 
\series bold
tractogram
\series default
.
 Tractograms provide a helpful and non-invasive form for inferring the connectiv
ity structure of the in-vivo white matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-tractography.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:tractography"

\end_inset

Graphic illustration of tractography.
 (a) Example dMRI data, also known as diffusion weighted imaging (DWI) data.
 (b) An individual streamline computed after performing tractography.
 (c) An example whole-brain tractogram that consists of streamlines covering
 the entire white matter.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-quantitative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some tractography algorithms are based on the intuitive principle of propagation.
 They start every streamline in a random seed located in the white matter
 and propagate a line by following the local dominant diffusion orientation,
 see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:streamline-tractogram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Pioneer algorithms of this type were implemented by taking information
 from the diffusion tensor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-2,tractography-3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, the PDD of the tensor is used as it is linked to the maximum
 diffusion direction, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:streamline-tractogram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, it is necessary to define when streamlines have to finish
 propagating.
 For this, a termination criterion is required.
 In some algorithms, streamlines propagation terminates when they reach
 a region with low anisotropy like gray matter, where there is no coherent
 direction to follow.
 Thus, a FA threshold is set to determine when streamlines are in an isotropic
 region.
 Typically, that threshold for tracking termination is set equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2$
\end_inset

 as FA in the gray matter is in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0.1,0.2\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Nonetheless, there are more termination criterion that can considered,
 for example, the angle change between pixels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-streamline-tractogram.png
	scale 25

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:streamline-tractogram"

\end_inset

Illustration of the main diffusion directions (black arrows) forming a vector
 field.
 (a) A streamline 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\left\{ \boldsymbol{p}_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{8}$
\end_inset

 (red arrow) is shown following the vector field.
 It can be seen how the streamline is composed of points in the space (red
 points).
 (b) A tractogram 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\left\{ s_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 different streamlines obtained by pursuing the maximum diffusivity direction.
 (c) Illustration of how the diffusion tensor can be used to represent the
 dominant diffusion direction.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tracking algorithms based on DTI have an important limitation handling voxels
 with multiple crossing fascicles, which leads to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pancake
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 shape rather than elongated tensors, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DTI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In these cases, the main diffusivity direction is not well defined.
 Thus, DTI tracking techniques produces streamlines that are not anatomically
 plausible (
\series bold
false positives
\series default
).
 With this in mind, HARDI 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 data and new methods like spherical deconvolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SD,CSD,MSMT-CSD,tractography-active-development-1,tractography-active-development-2,tractography-active-development-3,tractography-active-development-4,tractography-active-development-5,tractography-active-development-6,tractography-active-development-7,tractography-active-development-8,tractography-active-development-9,tractography-active-development-10,tractography-active-development-11,tractography-active-development-12"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, have allowed to detect crossing fascicles within a voxel for a more robust
 tractography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-csd-better-than-dti"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Notwithstanding, HARDI fiber tracking techniques have not solved all the
 tractography hitches.
 Moreover, HARDI techniques also have some limitations.
 For example, it cannot differentiate between crossing, kissing, or branching
 fascicles configurations, and some acquisition times are still too long
 for clinic applications, among others.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Propagating algorithms constitute a whole family of 
\series bold
local
\series default
 tracking techniques.
 The difference between them is how they use the local information to reconstruc
t the streamlines.
 Furthermore, several alternative tractography algorithms have been proposed,
 and they can be cataloged in different families.
 For instance, 
\series bold
global
\series default
 tracking techniques simultaneously fit the entire tractogram to all image
 data by iteratively perturbing a set of candidate trajectories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-global-8,tractography-global-9,tractography-global-10,tractography-global-11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, or progressively forming linked chains from a large set of randomly-initialize
d short streamline segments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-global-1,tractography-global-2,tractography-global-3,tractography-global-4,tractography-global-5,tractography-global-6,tractography-global-7"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:global-tractography"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, front evolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-active-development-6,tractography-front-evolution-1,tractography-front-evolution-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, geodesic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-geodesic-1,tractography-geodesic-2,tractography-geodesic-3,tractography-geodesic-4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and machine learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-machine-learning-1,tractography-machine-learning-2,tractography-machine-learning-3,tractography-machine-learning-4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 algorithms are current in development.
 Despite a large number of studies has been published, where different tractogra
phy algorithms are compared 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractography-review-1,tractography-review-2,tractography-review-3,tractography-review-4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, there is no a definitive algorithm to track the white matter.
 That's one of the reasons tractography, as field of study, is ample and
 currently active.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-global-tractography.png
	scale 45

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:global-tractography"

\end_inset

Example of the steps performed in the Gibbs tracking technique to simultaneously
 fit a whole tractogram to the dMRI data.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gibbs-tracking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to remark that streamlines do not represent real axonal
 tracts, but they represent the most plausible path of water diffusion.
 Besides, tractography is sensitive to the chosen tracking algorithm, i.e.
 quantitative analyses may be affected by the underlying algorithm or the
 parameters (seeds, stop criterion, etc.).
 Taking everything into account, caution must be taken when drawing conclusions
 on brain connectivity or brain functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Tractometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When tractography reconstructions and metrics derived from diffusion quantificat
ion are combined, the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tractometry
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractometry-1,tractometry-2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In tractometry, diffusion metrics are typically averaged over the tracts
 of interest, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:tractometry-example"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-tractometry-example.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:tractometry-example"

\end_inset

The fixel-based metric map has an image per every direction.
 Tractometry Ilustration.
 The voxel value of the rightest image is the mean of the values of the
 metric map
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis of these metrics along the tracts is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tract profiles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tractometry-3,tractometry-4,tractometry-5"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 types of tractometry reported in the literature: One that considers metrics
 derived from dMRI, while the others consider metrics from modalities other
 than dMRI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Phantoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Either in neuroscience research or clinical applications, validation is
 a requirement.
 Estimation of the fiber tracts and tissue profiles is extremely challenging.
 Besides, it is well-known that there is no in-vivo data with a real ground
 truth (GT) that could be used for validation.
 An extensively and successfully substitute for in-vivo GT is the use of
 synthetic phantoms.
 They constitute a controllable scenario that provides precise information
 of the underlying microstructural properties (e.g.
 local fiber orientation, geometrical configuration of fiber tracts, tissue
 properties, etc.).
 There are plenty of phantoms in the state-of-the-art that serve as validation
 tools for quantitatively and qualitatively evaluation of the performance
 of tractography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phantoms-compilation-for-tractography"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and microstructural estimation of diffusion MRI metrics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phantoms-compilation-for-dMRI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Phantoms can be classified into two groups: physical and digital phantoms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Physical Phantoms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to build hardware objects with arrangements of fibers crafted
 using synthetic, natural or glass fibers filled or soaked in a liquid 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "physical-phantom-1,physical-phantom-2,physical-phantom-3,physical-phantom-4,physical-phantom-5,physical-phantom-6,physical-phantom-7,physical-phantom-8,physical-phantom-9,physical-phantom-10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This emulates the water diffusion in restricted tissue.
 These phantoms can be imaged using a magnetic resonance scanner to get
 a diffusion-weighted signal because they are real world objects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-physical-phantom.jpg
	scale 41.5

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of 
\begin_inset Formula $90Â°$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $45Â°$
\end_inset

 physical phantoms resulting from a manual wiring of acrylic fibers (outer
 diameter of 
\begin_inset Formula $17$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

) inside a container incorporating the negative mask of the target fiber
 bundles.
 Image taken from 
