	filename fig-digital-phantom-3.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Illustration the 71 tracts used for the 99 brains Fiberfox simulation (a),
 exemplary axial slices of one simulated subject of the 99 brains dataset
 with various artifacts (b), and an exemplary phantom with randomized bundle
 configuration generated using Fiberfox (c).
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phantoms-compilation-for-tractography"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both physical and digital phantoms have their own advantages and limitations
 according to the use-cases.
 The most important difference between them is that even with a well defined
 physical phantom, it is not possible to provide such a perfect ground truth
 because of, for example, mechanical limitations or the statistical nature
 of the diffusion process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "phantoms-compilation-for-tractography"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, digital phantoms are the only way to obtain a dMRI data with a real
 ground truth.
 That's why we have decided to use a digital phantom for this work.
 We will discuss the selected phantom in the next chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Multiple Sclerosis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiple Sclerosis (MS) is a common neurological disease that affects primarily
 young adults.
 Usually, persons between the ages of 15 and 50 (average of 30) are affected
 by MS.
 It is present 2-3 times more often in women rather than men.
 However, the reasons are still unclear.
 MS begins with episodic attacks of neurological symptoms.
 Then some years later, it enters in a progressive phase.
 MS may have different stages after the first symptoms appear.
 For example, a 
\series bold
relapsing-remitting
\series default
 stage, which consists of attacks and remissions of symptoms.
 Many patients will later make the transition to a 
\series bold
secondary-progressive
\series default
 stage or they could begin with a 
\series bold
primary-progressive
\series default
 stage with slow progression without attacks.
 Recently, there has been some patients that began as progressive, but later
 they have one or more acute relapses.
 These cases are called 
\series bold
progressive-relapsing
\series default
 type of the MS disease.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the cause of MS is unclear, it is well-known that MS is not a 1-factor
 disease, but multiple factors are involved.
 Some factors like genetics (e.g.
 HLA DRB1*15:01), environmental (e.g.
 low vitamin D levels) and lifestyle (e.g.
 cigarette smoking) contribute to the development of MS.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inflammatory processes in the Central Nervous System (CNS) characterized
 by breakdown in the myelin that surrounds axon nerves.
 Breakdowns in the blood-brain barriers allows immunologically active cells
 in the blood to enter the brain and cause patchy damage to myelin.
 These scattered circumscribed lesions are called 
\series bold
plaques
\series default
 and cause the symptoms of MS slowing or disrupting conduction in the axons
 as myelin is necessary for the conduction in myelinated nerves.
 The plaques are characterized by inflammation, demyelination and scarring
 (
\series bold
gliosis
\series default
).
 Some axons can remyelinate again causing some remissions after an attack.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inflammation and gliosis are evident on Diffusion Magnetic Resonance Imaging
 (dMRI) scans 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "multiple-sclerosis-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:multiple-sclerosis-images"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The dMRI showing lesions in some areas, and the spinal fluid tests are
 helpful in diagnosing MS.
 However, they do not correlate with specific symptoms.
 That's why they are not used to follow the course of the disease once the
 diagnosis has been made.
 More importantly, they do not make themselves the diagnosis because similar
 changes can occur on other conditions.
 Finally, the presence of characteristic changes on the dMRI images raised
 a massive number of studies and analyses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-multiple-sclerosis-images-1.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\;$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-multiple-sclerosis-images-2.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:multiple-sclerosis-images"

\end_inset

Different imaging features in MS.
 (A, B) Axial fluid-attenuated inversion recovery (FLAIR) shows typical
 appearance of deep WM plaques like multiple hyperintense lesions in subcortical
 and cerebral deep WM, mostly ovoid in shape.
 (C, D) Sagittal FLAIR shows demyelinating plaques along the margin of lateral
 ventricles and the corpus callosum, with the typical radial arrangement,
 called Dawson fingers.
 Axial T1-weighted images before (E) and after (F) gadolinium administration
 show a single plaque in the right frontal lobe, which shows enhancement
 after contrast injection, consistent acute inflammatory demyelination.
 (G) Diffusion-weighted imaging reveals a high signal lesion, which may
 be related to the acute phase of the disease.
 Images taken from 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://radiologykey.com/diffusion-magnetic-resonance-imaging-in-multiple-scleros
is
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Itemize
The hallmark of multiple sclerosis is the focal lesions, which are distributed
 diffusely in the brain.
 Lesions are areas with a high degree of demyelination and axonal degeneration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiple Sclerosis (MS) is recurrent demyelinating disease of the white
 matter in the Central Nervous System (CNS), which usually becomes progressive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This affects the remaining part of the NAWM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some lesions don't show constrast.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

